    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <h3>What is deep learning and how does it differ from traditional machine learning?</h3>
    <p>Deep learning uses neural networks with many layers to automatically learn hierarchical representations from raw data. Traditional ML typically requires manual feature engineering — you decide what to measure. Deep learning learns what to measure directly from images, text, or audio. The tradeoff: deep learning needs far more data and compute, but achieves dramatically better results on complex perceptual tasks.</p>

    <h3>Why does deep learning require so much data and compute?</h3>
    <p>Deep networks have millions to billions of parameters that must be tuned through backpropagation across large training datasets. More parameters mean more capacity to learn complex patterns, but also more data required to avoid overfitting and more compute to run the optimization. GPUs accelerate this because matrix multiplications — the core operation — parallelize extremely well on GPU hardware.</p>

    <h3>What is transfer learning and how does it reduce cost?</h3>
    <p>Transfer learning reuses a model pre-trained on a large dataset (e.g., ImageNet, internet text) as a starting point for a new task. Instead of training from scratch, you fine-tune a fraction of the parameters on your smaller dataset. This reduces training time, compute cost, and data requirements dramatically — and often produces better results than training from scratch on limited data. See <a href={`${base}/chapters/09-fine-tuning`}>Chapter 9</a> for LLM fine-tuning specifics.</p>

    <h3>When should my team use a pre-trained model vs. train from scratch?</h3>
    <p>Pre-trained models (from Hugging Face, PyTorch Hub, or major AI labs) are the right default for most teams. Build from scratch only when your data is fundamentally different from anything public (rare medical imagery, proprietary sensor data) and you have the resources to exceed state-of-the-art. For most enterprise use cases, fine-tuning or prompting a pre-trained model is faster, cheaper, and produces better results.</p>

    <h3>What is a GPU and why is it essential for deep learning?</h3>
    <p>A GPU (Graphics Processing Unit) was originally designed for rendering graphics by performing thousands of simple calculations in parallel. Deep learning training involves the same type of parallel matrix math. Modern GPUs (NVIDIA H100, A100) can perform this computation orders of magnitude faster than CPUs. Cloud GPU instances (AWS, Azure, GCP) have made this compute accessible without large capital investment.</p>

